<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="73">(Ekman H.14847, Ekman H.15042, Ekman H.15102</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="73">Abbott 2922),</emphasis>
only one 
<emphasis box="[1045,1244,924,950]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="73">(Ekman H15102)</emphasis>
is fertile. The sheet in S (
<figureCitation box="[932,1015,957,983]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[181,215,1854,1875]" captionTargetBox="[234,1383,205,1826]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. a, lectotype of Solanum chamaeacanthum Griseb., Wright s.n. (GOET0001971); b, lectotype of S. hoplophorum O.E. Schulz, Fuertes 1023 (S04-2916) (= S.crotonoides Lam.).Reproduced with permission of the Swedish Museum of Natural History; c, lectotype of S. formonense O.E. Schulz and of S. formonense var. parvifolium O.E. Schulz,Ekman H.10265 (S04-2911) (= S. crotonoides Lam.). Reproduced with permission of the Swedish Museum of Natural History; d, lectotype of S. dendroicum O.E.Schulz &amp; Ekman, Ekman H.15102 (S04-2902). Reproduced with permission of the Swedish Museum of Natural History." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6326312" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6326312/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="73">Fig. 2d</figureCitation>
) has been chosen as the lectotype because Eric Ekman’s top set of specimens is housed in Stockholm, all have been annotated by Ekman, and S04-2902 is in excellent condition.
</paragraph>
